Yes, that’s a good way to describe one aspect of it, with a small refinement.

Flowers and many insects have evolved a mutualistic relationship in which reproduction is tightly coupled:

* The flower “wants” pollen moved to another flower of the same species.
* The insect “wants” nectar or pollen as food.
* Neither consciously intends to reproduce the other, yet their interactions frequently accomplish exactly that.

In that sense, they’re participating in each other’s reproductive success without intending to. Evolution has shaped traits on both sides—flower color, scent, nectar guides, bloom timing, insect vision, mouthparts, and behavior—so the interaction becomes highly reliable.

You could say:

Flowers and pollinating insects have an evolutionarily co-adapted reproductive relationship. Each pursues its own immediate goals, yet together they enable one another’s evolutionary success.

It’s a nice example of how evolution often builds systems where local incentives create global outcomes. The bee isn’t trying to help the flower reproduce; the flower isn’t trying to feed the bee out of generosity. Their evolved traits align well enough that both generally benefit.

There are also interesting exceptions. Some orchids mimic female insects in appearance or scent, causing males to attempt mating (called pseudocopulation), transferring pollen without providing a nectar reward. That shows the relationship isn’t always cooperative—it can include deception as well.